I"í<h2 id="solution">Solution:</h2>

<p>We solve the recurrence for a few values of $n$ to get a feel for it.</p>

\[\begin{alignat*}{2}
        T(1) &amp;= 1 \\ \\
        T(2) &amp;= T(1) + \frac{n}{2} &amp;&amp;= \frac{n + 2}{2} \\ \\
        T(3) &amp;= T(2) + \frac{n}{2} &amp;&amp;= \frac{2n + 2}{2} \\ \\
        T(4) &amp;= T(5) + \frac{n}{2} &amp;&amp;= \frac{3n + 2}{2} \\ \\
        T(5) &amp;= T(4) + \frac{n}{2} &amp;&amp;= \frac{4n + 2}{2}        
    \end{alignat*}\]

<p>Hence, we propose that</p>

\[T(n) = \frac{n + 2}{2} + \frac{(n - 2)n}{2} = \frac{n^2 - n + 2}{2}\]

<p>We can now prove this via induction on $n$. For the base case, consider $n = 1$. Clearly,</p>

\[T(1) = \frac{1^2 - 1 + 2}{2} = \frac{2}{2} = 1\]

<p>For the inductive hypothesis (IH), assume that for all $k &lt; n$,</p>

\[T(k) = \frac{k^2 - k + 2}{2}\]

<p>Now, for the inductive step, we have</p>

\[\begin{align*}
        T(n) = T(n - 1) + \frac{n}{2} \text{ (by definition of $T(n)$) }       
    \end{align*}\]
